```Explanations
Potentiometer: The linear potentiometer is used to convert the pendulum's angular position into an electrical signal (voltage). With a range of 45 to 135 degrees, the potentiometer provides a variable resistance corresponding to the angle of the pendulum. The potentiometer should have a good linearity over the specified range to ensure accurate angle measurement.

Buffer Amplifier: The potentiometer's output is connected to a buffer amplifier. The objective of this block is to provide a low-impedance output without loading the potentiometer. This ensures the voltage accurately represents the position of the pendulum without being affected by the subsequent circuitry.

Scaling Amplifier: Since the DAQ can only accept a maximum of +/- 7 V and the potentiometer is powered by -10 to +10 V, a scaling amplifier is necessary to scale down the potentiometer signal to fall within the acceptable input range of the DAQ. This amplifier will also ensure any necessary gain adjustments for the potentiometer signal while preserving linearity.

Low-Pass Filter (50/60 Hz Notch): This filter is designed to attenuate unwanted frequencies, particularly the 50 and 60 Hz signals which can be common in electrical noise due to power lines. This improves the signal quality before digitization and ensures no interference from these frequencies.

Anti-Aliasing Filter: An anti-aliasing filter is a low-pass filter placed before the DAQ input to remove high-frequency components that could cause aliasing when the signal is sampled by the DAQ. The filter's cutoff frequency should be slightly less than half the DAQ's sampling rate, as per the Nyquist theorem, to ensure accurate digital representation of the analog signal.

DAQ Input: This is the interface to the Data Acquisition system (DAQ) which digitizes the conditioned analog signal. The DAQ's specifications, including its maximum voltage level and whether it accepts single-ended or differential input, determine the final signal conditioning requirements not specified in this project.
